Today's session was about OSI MODEL 

Today I dove into how the internet actually works. I learned about the OSI Model. At first it sounded complicated. Its basically the rulebook for how computers talk to each other.
Whenever I send an email or stream a video my data doesn't just magically appear. It gets packed, shipped and unpacked through 7 layers before it reaches the persons screen.
A great trick to memorize the layers is: Please Do Not Throw Sausage Pizza
Here's what happens at each stage:
Layer 1: The Physical Layer
What it is: The hardware. This includes copper cables, Wi-Fi radio waves and fiber optics.
How it works: It sends data as bits over a physical medium. This layer doesn't know what the data means; it just pushes signals from point A to point B.

Layer 2: The Data Link Layer 
What it is: The local delivery system.
How it works: It takes bits and packages them into frames. This is where device addresses live. Network switches operate here making sure a frame gets to the device in the same network.

Layer 3: The Network Laye
What it is: The GPS of the internet. This layer routes data between networks.
How it works: It takes frames. Turns them into packets adding IP addresses. Routers live here. They find the path to send a packet.

Layer 4: The Transport Layer
What it is: The quality control manager.
How it works: It breaks data into segments. Dictates how its sent. It uses TCP or UDP. TCP ensures every piece arrives perfectly while UDP sends data fast but might drop some pieces.

Layer 5: The Session Layer 
What it is: The conversation coordinator.
How it works: This layer opens a "session" between my computer and a web server. It ensures the connection stays open to exchange data and closes it securely when done.

Layer 6: The Presentation Layer 
What it is: The translator.
How it works: It prepares data for software. It handles data formatting, compression and encryption. This layer scrambles passwords into code.

Layer 7: The Application Layer
What it is: The part I interact with!
How it works: This layer is closest to me. It's where web browsers, email clients and apps operate. Protocols, like HTTP and SMTP live here.
